USER: Show me a code snippet of a website's sticky header in CSS and JavaScript.
ASSISTANT: Sure, here is an example of how you can create a sticky header using CSS and JavaScript:

HTML:
```html
<header class="sticky-header">
  <nav>
    <!-- Your navigation links go here -->
  </nav>
</header>

<div id="content">
  <!-- The rest of your page content goes here -->
</div>
```

CSS:
```css
.sticky-header {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0; /* Sticks to the top */
  background-color: #333; /* Background color for header */
  padding: 10px; /* Padding around the header */
}

nav a {
  margin-right: 20px; /* Space between navigation links */
}
```

JavaScript:
```javascript
window.onscroll = function() {myFunction()};

var header = document.getElementById("content");
var sticky = header.offsetTop;

function myFunction() {
  if (window.pageYOffset > sticky) {
    header.classList.add("sticky-header");
  } else {
    header.classList.remove("sticky-header");
  }
}
```

This code will make the header stick to the top of the page when you scroll down. The JavaScript function `myFunction` checks if the user has scrolled past a certain point (the height of the sticky header), and then adds or removes the "sticky-header" class from the `<header>` element, which is defined in CSS.
